<font color="#FF0000">TIRED AGGIE!!!</font><br>
<tt>Sat Jul 26  4:14:19 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Tired Aggie<br><br>
Did I ever tell you about tired Aggie? <br><br>
Aggie was an outstanding A-gunner. During battles, he always laid on my right side because gooks like shooting A-gunners,  who they knew were always situated on the left side of the machine gunner. <br>
Aggie was a tall dark skinned, pock marked faced Mexican from Wilmington, California. He owned a Chevy with twice pipes. Everyone liked Aggie, but he was slow moving and could care less of rank and orders.<br>
Everything Aggie did was slow moving and he walked around this way like he didn't have a care in the world. <br><br>
One day he sprang his ankle and with the aid of our Platoon corpsmen, he milked it for almost two weeks. Dumont our squad leader had one day asked tired Aggie to fill four sandbags that he planned to use as supports for claymore mines he was going to set up later that eveing in front of our bunker. <br>
That was all that Aggie had to do that day, just fill four sandbags. <br>
When evening came Aggie still had not finished the job. He kept complaining about his ankle and walked with a limp to prove it. <br>
Unknown to Aggie, Dumont had earlier removed the powder from a grenade and then had replaced the spoon. <br><br>
After chow while we all sat around the hooch, listening to the sounds of Marvin Gay coming from the portable juice box, Dumont accidentally dropped the fake grenade inside the hooch. <br>
Tired Aggie sprang to his feet and cleared the bunker in seconds. <br>
When he saw us rolling in the bunker, laughing our heads off at the joke we had played on him. He scooped up a handful of mud and threw it at us. Within minutes we were all engaged in one of the messiest mud fights ever. <br>
About that time that word was passed for our gun team to settle up. We were going out on a night ambush. We went out that way, all dirty and full of mud. <br>
Later that night it rained. Long and hard rain, but I recall it as one of the warmest nights I ever spent out in the bush.  Somehow we all shared a great comfort in having Aggie with us again.<br><br>
Gosh I loved that guy. <br><br>

